title: SEP takes senior night to clinch title
text:
Southeast Polk high school Rams (Photo: The Register)
CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE The Southeast Polk girls volleyball team defeated Ankeny Centennial in a "Senior Night" home dual meet Oct. 13 to clinch the first CIC Eastern Division volleyball championship in school history. The Rams swept dual meet matches with Ankeny, Waukee and Ankeny Centennial during the regular season to claim the championship trophy.
The victory over Centennial did not come easy as the Jaguars opened the match with 25-21 and 25-11 wins in the first two games. But the Rams were not to be denied and rallied to win 25-21, 25-23 and 15-13 in the last three sets.
"Tonight was A LOT of fun. This is our first conference championship, EVER," coach Matt Parker said. "Our passing was really shaky in games one and two--not up to our par. I felt confident that if we could dial in our passing that we would have more success in game three, and that's exactly what happened. We grinded out a win in game three and got more confidence in game four. The fifth game swung back and forth and was tight all the way to the end. At 13-13, junior Maya Barker got a huge block to put us up 14-13. Game point was scored by a Carlee Beck dig off Ankeny's outside hitter and a big kill by Junior Emily Plock."
MVPs of the match were junior Nicole Majerus and senior Casey Stuart. Majerus had 15 kills on 29 swings and only 3 errors. Stuart had some key defensive digs, served very consistently and had four aces on the night.
Seniors Meghan Welsh, Sydnee Chiri, Haley Hesse, Sam Sixta, Casey Stuart, Lexa Sandquist, Jordan Travis, Carlee Beck, Sydney Rosenboom Taylor Doser, and Ireland Pollpeter appeared in their final regular season game for the Rams.
"It was a great evening to honor our 11 seniors. They will be leaving behind a legacy--first conference championship," Parker said.
After clinching their first conference championship in school history on Oct. 13, the Class 5A, No. 9 Rams battled to a 2-2 record at the Johnston Invitational on Oct. 17.
The Rams defeated Oskaloosa (2-0) and Ames (2-0) and lost to Class 5A, No. 8 WDM Valley (2-0) in pool play.
